Note that you're adding the 'disabled' class to the element, which by default, should prevent any further interactions (in this case, the click event) with the element. 

If you want to prioritize the click event over the 'disabled' state, you might need to reconsider the UI logic that allows clicking on a disabled element, especially considering accessibility guidelines.

Before you make this change, note that changing the class name to 'disabled' programmatically won't quite behave like a browser would in terms of ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) and non-visual accessibility.

A more maintainable way might be to simply reuse the class name (d-none) to visually change how the element is presented and remove it when you want the button to be visibly active again. 

