Apisauce is a popular library for handling API requests in React Native. To send a binary file as the body of a PUT request using Apisauce, you'll need to manually handle the request options and the binary data.

Here's an example of how you can do this:

```jsx
import Api from 'apisauce';

const api = Api.create({
  // base URL of your API
  baseUri: 'https://your-base-url.com/api',
  // headers etc
});

const binaryData = {
  binary: require('./path/to/your/binary/file'), // replace with your binary file path
};

const requestConfig = {
  method: 'PUT',
  url: '/your_PUT_endpoint',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/octet-stream', // for binary data
  },
  body: binaryData.binary, // pass the binary data
};

api.put(requestConfig)
 .then(response => {
    console.log(response.data);
  })
 .catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
  });
```

However, the above approach is not recommended as it will replace any headers in `Api.create()` definition. The items in the data and objects usually must not be entered blindly into any JSON object so they may look like follows:

```jsx
import Api from 'apisauce';

const api = Api.create({
  // base URL of your API
  baseUri: 'https://your-base-url.com/api',
  // headers etc
});

const binaryData = {
  file: {
    property1: 'value',
    file: {
      uri: Uri.file('./path/to/your/binary/file'),
      type: 'application/octet-stream',
      name: 'file_name.bin'
    }
  }
};

const requestConfig = {
  method: 'PUT',
  url: '/your_PUT_endpoint',
  headers: {
    'Content-Type': 'application/json; charset=utf8', // note the JSON header
  },
  data: binaryData.file // pass the wrapped binary data
};

api.put(requestConfig)
 .then(response => {
    console.log(response.data);
  })
 .catch(error => {
    console.error(error);
  });
```

Please ensure the correct path to your binary file and replace `Uri_file` with `android_uri_file`, if you are using both android and ios plugins mixed together. Try to do HTTP POST with original mime binary thing instead (insist HTTP api can carry PUT with_http method nonetheless).

To animate the shows from bottom left to top right instead of bottom right to top left, you can adjust the values in the `@keyframes trail` to apply the drop shadows in the opposite direction.

Here's how you can modify the `@keyframes trail` to achieve the desired animation:

```css
@keyframes trail {
  0% {
    filter: drop-shadow(30px 0px 30px gray); /* Apply a drop shadow from left to top */
  }
  100% {
    filter: drop-shadow(30px 0px 30px gray) drop-shadow(15px 15px 15px gray); /* Apply a drop shadow from left to top and another from top right to bottom left */
  }
}
```

In the modified code, I've adjusted the `30px 0px 30px gray` to apply the drop shadow from the left edge (x-axis) at the current y-axis position, effectively giving the illusion of the animation starting from the left. The second drop shadow remains unchanged to follow the existing behavior. 

Please note that you should keep in mind that changing the `animation-direction` property might also be necessary if you want to follow the standard "forward and backward" animation behavior. In this case, the corrected values above will result in the desired "bottom-left to top-right" animation behavior.

