Combiner code in Hadoop MapReduce is a optional stage between the Map and Reduce phases. The main purpose of the Combiner is to reduce the amount of data that needs to be transferred between the Map and Reduce phases, and hence reduce the overall processing time.

**What does the Combiner do?**

When the Map phase completes, the MapReduce framework sorts the output key-value pairs by the key and groups them together. The Combiner is then applied to each group of key-value pairs. The Combiner takes a group of key-value pairs as input, and produces a new set of key-value pairs as output. The Combiner is essentially a mini-version of the Reduce function.

**How does the Combiner help?**

The main advantage of using a Combiner is to reduce the amount of data that needs to be transferred between the Map and Reduce phases. When the Map output is large, the data transfer time can be significant. By applying a Combiner, we can aggregate the data at the mapper end itself and reduce the amount of data that needs to be transferred. This can greatly improve the performance of the system.

**How to implement Combiner code?**

To implement a Combiner code in Hadoop MapReduce, you need to create a new class that extends the `Reducer` class. This class will contain the implementation of the Combiner function. You can access the input key-value pairs from the group using the `context` object, and produce the output key-value pairs.

Here is an example implementation of a Combiner code:

```java
import org.apache.hadoop.io.IntWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.LongWritable;
import org.apache.hadoop.io.Text;
import org.apache.hadoop.mapreduce.Reducer;

public class CombinerExample extends Reducer<IntWritable, Text, IntWritable, Text> {
  @Override
  public void reduce(IntWritable key, Iterable<Text> values, Context context)
      throws IOException, InterruptedException {
    // aggregate the values associated with the key
    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
    for (Text value : values) {
      sb.append(value.toString()).append(",");
    }
    context.write(key, new Text(sb.toString()));
  }
}
```

