In Tailwind CSS and React, you can use the `flex` utility class to create flexible container layouts. Here's a basic example:

```jsx
import React from'react';

function Example() {
  return (
    <div className="flex justify-center items-center h-screen">
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4 text-white">Centered content</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, `.flex` is applied to the outer container, making it a flexible container. The `justify-center` class is used to justify the content horizontally, and `items-center` is used to align the content vertically.

However, if you want to use the `flex` utility as a prop on a React component, you can use the `style` attribute or the `className` attribute (as shown above) with the utility class name.

If you are using mode "styled-components" the code may look something like this:

```jsx
import React from'react';
import { styled } from'styled-components';

const Container = styled.div`
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  height: 100vh;
`;

function Example() {
  return (
    <Container>
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4 text-white">Centered content</div>
    </Container>
  );
}
```

If you're using raw React without styled components, you could use function like this:

```jsx
import React from'react';

function Container(props) {
  return (
    <div style={{
      display: "flex",
      justifyContent: "center",
      alignItems: "center",
      height: "100vh"
    }}>
      {props.children}
    </div>
  );
}

function Example() {
  return (
    <Container>
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4 text-white">Centered content</div>
    </Container>
  );
}
```

Note: Always make sure to follow the syntax provided in the [official documentation](https://tailwindcss.com/docs-flex) of Tailwind CSS to use the `flex` utility class effectively.

To use `order-last` and `self-center` with Flex in Tailwind CSS, you can apply the utility classes to the child elements of the Flex container.

`order-last` is used to set the order of the child elements, and `self-center` (or `self-auto`) is used to center the child elements belonging to the same Flex line.

Here's an example:

```jsx
import React from'react';

function Example() {
  return (
    <div className="flex justify-between">
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4 text-white">First element</div>
      <div className="bg-blue-500 p-4 text-white order-last self-center">Second element</div>
      <div className="bg-green-500 p-4 text-white">Third element</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, we apply `order-last` to the second child element so that it appears last in the Flex container. We also apply `self-center` to center this child element.

However, in order to have a Flex item (within a flex line) being self-centered while at the same time not having its order being "auto", you need to define in the parent a "flex-grow" property.

Here is an example where we apply both `order-last` and `self-center` along with `flex-grow` like this:

```jsx
import React from'react';

function Example() {
  return (
    <div className="flex justify-between items-center space-x-2">
      <div className="bg-gray-500 flex-grow">First element</div>
      <div className="bg-red-500 p-4 text-white cursor-pointer">✎</div>
      <div className="bg-green-500 flex-grow order-last self-center">Second element</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Note that, we used both `justify-between` and `items-center` to have self-centered children and equal spacing at the same time.

