Yes, you can encrypt text using a key and output as a string in C++. Here's a simple example using the Caesar Cipher technique. This is a basic substitution cipher where each letter in the plaintext is'shifted' a certain number of places down the alphabet.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

// Function to encrypt the string
std::string encrypt(const std::string& plaintext, int key) {
    std::string ciphertext = "";
    for (char c : plaintext) {
        if (isalpha(c)) {
            char asciiOffset = isupper(c)? 65 : 97;
            ciphertext += chr((c - asciiOffset + key) % 26 + asciiOffset);
        } else {
            ciphertext += c;
        }
    }
    return ciphertext;
}

// Function to convert character to ASCII value (maps 1-26 to 97-122)
char chr(int value) {
    return value + 96;
}

// Function to convert ASCII value to character (maps 97-122 to 1-26)
char chr(int value) {
    return value - 96;
}

int main() {
    std::string plaintext = "Hello, World!";
    int key = 3;
    std::string ciphertext = encrypt(plaintext, key);

    std::cout << "Plaintext: " << plaintext << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Key: " << key << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Ciphertext: " << ciphertext << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

This example uses the ASCII values of the characters to perform the encryption. For uppercase letters, it uses the values from 65 to 90 (A-Z), and for lowercase letters, it uses the values from 97 to 122 (a-z).

Please note that this is a basic example and real-world encryption would be much more complex and secure.

If you want to use a more robust encryption algorithm like AES, you might want to look into libraries like OpenSSL or CrypToy for C++.

