```cpp
#include <iostream>

const int N = 5; // Define the size of the array

// Function to calculate factorial
int factorial(int num) {
    if (num == 0)
        return 1;
    else
        return num * factorial(num - 1);
}

int main() {
    int arr[N]; // Create an array of size 5

    // Calculate factorial for each number and store it in the array
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        arr[i] = factorial(i);
        std::cout << "Factorial of " << i << " is: " << arr[i] << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This code defines a function `factorial` that calculates the factorial of a given number `num`. The `main` function then creates an array of size 5, calculates the factorial for each number from 0 to 4, and stores the result in the array. Finally, it prints the factorial of each number.

When you run this code, it will output the following:

```
